        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Aug 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>The almond tree which you gave me has produced no fruit; but the Double Chinese Peach has 3 fruit.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Now, if you have any bearing Almond trees, would you have kindness, when fruit ripe to send me 2 or 3; &amp; if you have any other <hi rend="doubleUnderline">odd</hi> peach 2 or 3 to compare the stones.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> The best address is</p> 
<figure type="diagram"> 
<p>“C. Darwin”</p>
<p>“care of Down Postman”</p>
<p><hi rend="underline">per Rail</hi> “Bromley”</p>
<p>“Kent”</p> </figure> 
<p>I presume you have no more facts for me to quote on inheritance of weeping trees; you said, if you had time, you could prove the weeping elm.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>Now I am going to beg another favour. Have you yourself seen any kind of modification in fruit or foliage any fruit-tree from being grafted. Andrew Knight &amp; others assert that slight differences do result;<ref target="#foot.f5"/> others positively deny this. Can you give me any certain facts?<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p>
<p>Lastly I ask on mere improbable chance of the point having occurred to you: viz do you believe &amp; can you any how account for the positive statements of several good pears (&amp; several varieties of wheat) having been discovered as seedlings in hedges &amp; woods. On mere doctrine of chances, this might perhaps have occasionally occurred; but the occurrence seems too frequent for mere chance. I have not yet collected such recorded cases, as I have met with, but I know that I have several. &amp; in a day or two shall collect them.<ref target="#foot.f7"/> </p>
<p>Pray excuse me thus troubling you, &amp; believe me, My dear Sir | Yours sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
